thenticity and difference. In this compelling work of cultural history, O’Malley interprets a stunning array of historical sources to evaluate the comingling of ideas about monetary value and social distinctions. More than just a history, Face Value offers us a new way of thinking about the present culture of coded racism, gold fetishism, and economic uncertainty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxPublic opinionxHistory. 0aEqualityxEconomic aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMonetary policyxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMoneyxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMoneyzUnited StatesxPsychological aspectsxHistory. 0aPublic opinionzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022662937740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226629391423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226629391/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles